Comment: I've been slowly creeping up the slow ladder and have now reached the point where I am seen as "easy meat" for some of the higher ranked players. Usually I oblige by making a daft move. Sometimes however my opponent gets stiffer opposition than they expect. This is one of those rare games and I was very pleased with the outcome.
I start with the Kings gambit as this is something I have played quite a bit recently with some success. My theory is that its not seen so often and so it takes some players out of their comfort zone

Now black looks to be in a bit of bother, the main threat being Ne6 winning the queen

The knight is immune as taking it loses to Qg5+, Kh7, Qg7#. The black queen doesn't have many useful places to go due to the combination above, the exception is Qf8 which exchanges the queen for a knight (or bishop). The move I was expecting was Nh7 which holds off mate but loses the queen

This is a decent try from black as the temptation of Qxh6 lets the black queen off the hook

I wasn't sure here whether to try to extract my knight or to simply go for an exchange. I decided on the latter as I can double black's pawns on c which not only hampers him but means his a8 rook can be tied down to defending his a pawn while his other rook is hemmed in.
